<font color="#FF0000">PACIFISTS AND CONTRABAND</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct 29  6:56:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
An interesting post which reminds me that we never fully addressed the topic of the American Friends Service and their role in Vietnam.<br><br>
We had talked about this a couple of months ago and I had requested sources from you. We sort of got sidetracked from this and a couple of other issues.<br><br>
I don't profess to know a great deal about the role of American Friends, although I did come in contact with several while in RVN.<br><br>
As far as them providing medical treatment, in their facilities, for wounded enemy soldiers as you mentioned a while ago; I have no reason to doubt it. I would venture to say that people who are Apolitical, with a humanitarian mission, fail to see *our* enemy as *their* enemy. Our opinions may run counter to that, but their beliefs are not dependent on our approval.<br><br>
SW made some strong points as to how pacifists enjoyed the security and freedom that was provided by soldiers who fought and died to guarantee them. I can illustrate another seeming hypocrisy on the part of the American Friends. I knew a Quaker woman who was working in Quang Ngai City, and was about to give birth. She planned on having her baby in Chu Lai at the military hospital!<br><br>
It would be interesting to see how the food and medical supplies got into the hands of the VC/NVA. Again, I don't doubt that this happened.<br><br>
In early June 1970 our company was securing a pacification ville called Tra Binh. On two nights we were hit by heavy mortar and RPG attacks. When we were policing the area afterwards, many of the tailfin assemblies were the 81mm variety - which were distinctly different from the communist's 82's. I often wondered how our enemy received these rounds. I am not talking about 2 or 3 that may have been captured. The first night alone we received about 80 incoming rounds. About 1/3 were NATO 81mm.<br><br>
So are we to deduce that the US Government was deliberately supplying our enemy simply because we could ID the source of the ammunition?<br><br>
You know, as well as I, that there existed a huge black market in Vietnam. One lesser illustration was that at the time I was in Americal, we had to purchase, for 5 bucks, regular GI Issue Bush Hats from the Vietnamese in the village! These should have been issued to us for free! Yet, someone had sold them all to the Vietnamese. This may seem innocuous compared to the matter of ammunition, but it still shows how it was possible for GI's to fall victim to someone else's bad intentions.<br><br>
I can only surmise that much of the materiel you are referring to was possibly sent via Hanoi or Haiphong for use in those areas, and was diverted south by the communists.<br><br>
Again, I prefer to believe that whatever medicine and food sentby any pacifist organization was for humanitarian purposes and not political. Unfortunately good intentions are often distorted by someone else's bad intentions.
<p><code>-- wingman#greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


